Syrian Civil War Refugee and Host Country Characteristics¶

Overview¶

Video Link: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_cVRzEtX0ho

The Syrian Civil War has caused a large outflow of refugees into countries all over the world. Especially notable are the host nations bordering the country who hold the most refugees from this internal conflict. To figure out the basic demographics of the Syrian refugee population, we performed basic data processing and visualization tasks. As for determining significant measures that Syrian refugees may take a look at when settling in a host country, we applied a linear regression and correlation analysis to determine which features strongly correlate with a higher refugee population count. With about 5.6 million Syrian refugees in the countries neighboring Syria, most of them being male, we found that a large portion of them were minors who make up 46% of the male refugee population and 48% of the female refugee population. With four nations to pick from, we found that nations who were a signatory of the 1951 Refugee Convention, had a higher population size, had a higher Gross Domestic Product (GDP), and had higher rates of kidnapping were highly associated with taking in more refugees whereas nations who had more events in terms of fatalities, explosions/remote violence and battles had a strong negative correlation with refugee influx into a country.

Research Question¶

What internal demographic differences and events are present among displaced Syrian refugees and the nations where they flee? Are there any apparent trends among refugee and asylum seekers’ migration to bordering nations?

Background & Prior Work¶

In the modern socio-political climate refugee and asylum seekers comprise one of the most vulnerable and one of the fastest growing populations. A 2021 study of refugee and asylum seekers by the United Nations indicated that a record number 84 million refugees had been displaced in the time period between January 2021 and November 2021 [^UN2]. Current projections show the effects of climate change, the COVID-19 Pandemic and governmental instability exacerbating this already growing trend throughout the 2020s. Understanding refugee patterns and the taken towards resettlement is key to being properly prepared and integrating them into host countries. Representing the largest and longest refugee crisis of the 2010s, an analysis of refugee data from the Syrian Civil War can provide insights on how governments and NGOs can better prepare for future global crises.

Following the most intense drought in modern Syrian history from 2006 to 2010, the largely agrarian population had resettled into urban ghettos. Following the period of resettlement, disturbed populations began to protest inequitable economic policy as well as the complacent Assad regime [^Brit]. Military response to the peaceful protests seen throughout the region sparked what has become a decade long civil war for control of Syria. The Civil War has seen over 6.6 million registered Syrian refugees leave the country [^UN].

References: [^Brit]: Britannica, The Editors of Encyclopaedia. "Syrian Civil War". Encyclopedia Britannica, 17 Jul. 2020, https://www.britannica.com/event/Syrian-Civil-War. Accessed 21 April 2022. Hypothesis¶

Our team believes that refugees of the Syrian civil war will be skewed towards women, children, and the elderly. We believe that conscription and pressure to volunteer will result in men ages 18-35 remaining in the country. Furthermore we believe that politically calm and more stable nations will attract more refugees than other nations. While they are ultimately looking to flee from prosecution to relative safety, social programs and political stability will attract refugees.

Data Cleaning¶

We obtained our datasets from sites including ACLED and data2, and these datasets had varying numbers of observations. The data that we obtained from ACLED had many columns that were not necessary or usable for our data analysis, so we went through each column to find what we did and did not need, and then created a subset of the dataframe that included only the event date, event type, country that the event occurred in, and the number of fatalities. This data was already saved in a csv file, so we only had to upload it to the repo in order to access it. Furthermore, since we only want to look at violent events in addition to protests, we dropped all of the rows that had events categorized as "strategic developments". Afterwards, we checked if there were any null values within the dataframe, but there were none that appeared.

For the dataset that includes the total persons of concern by country of asylum, the site that we pulled the data from did not have an accessible csv file. Because of this, we had to access the data as JSON and then use a JSON to csv converter, where we were then able to download and load in the data. Similarly to the data we obtained from ACLED, there were many columns that were not necessary for our analysis, so we created a subset of the dataframe which reduced it from 78 columns to 2. Following that, we dropped the observations for Egypt and other countries including North Africa as they are not bordering Syria. Lastly, we added a new column to this dataframe called "Benefits", referring to the legal framework available for Syrian Refugees to obtain citizenship and other benefits in these countries. We obtained this data by looking into which countries were signatories of the 1951 Refugee Convention which is a legal system on refugee rights. We quantified the legal framework by assigning the value of 1 to countries that were signatories, and 0 to countries that were not.

Furthermore, the dataset that includes the different age groups and genders was also pulled from data2 which did not have an accessible csv file, so we once again used a converter. When we loaded in the data, we noticed that there was only 1 row and 109 columns. Because the data was formatted like this, we rearranged the data so that Male and Female were the observations (rows), and the different age groups were the columns. We also dropped the unnecessary columns. The column names were not easy to read, so we renamed them to make them more intuitive. Lastly, we took the totals among the rows and created a new column with the total values.

# selecting certain rows in male dataset based on Region, subregion, country or area * column
male = male[male['Region, subregion, country or area *'].isin(['Iraq', 'Lebanon', 'Jordan', 'Turkey'])]

# subsetting data (first round to remove notes column)
male = male.drop(columns = 'Notes')

# drop all rows which have a null value
male = male.dropna(axis = 0)

# selecting largest years by each Region, subregion, country or area *
male = male.sort_values('Reference date (as of 1 July)').groupby('Region, subregion, country or area *').tail(1)

# subsetting data
male = male.iloc[:, 2:]
male.drop(male.columns[[1,2,3,4]], axis = 1, inplace = True)

# convert the columns besides Region, subregion, country or area * into numeric
for col in male.columns[1:]:
    male[col] = pd.to_numeric(male[col], errors='coerce')

# sum up all of the ages into one population for gender
male['total'] = male.sum(axis = 1, numeric_only = True)

# subsetting data
male = male[['Region, subregion, country or area *', 'total']]

# renaming columns to add to large dataset later
male.columns = ['country', 'male']

These factors would artificially manipulate migrant inflows potentially resulting in the abnormal data present.

Ethics & Privacy¶

Our project is being done purely for academic purposes, and all of the datasets that we pull from are publicly available. Additionally, the entries from these datasets are unmodified, and are analyzed directly from the CSV files. We would also like to address that while we attempted to include as many factors that could potentially affect the resettlement relocation of Syrian refugees, we may be missing other factors that could have higher predictive values. This could have an unintended consequence of someone misusing our findings as they may not be completely comprehensive. Furthermore, these datasets are pulled from websites including UNICEF, UNHCR, and ACLED, in which the data should be confirmed before making any declarative statements or other assumptions as there may be inconsistencies.

Additionally, there are also privacy concerns for those who view our project and want to access the datasets that we used. Some of these sites may collect personal information such as names, postal address, email addresses, telephone numbers, social media names, contact preferences, gender, date of birth, etc. While some sites may collect standard information such as an IP address or computer ID, others require the user to sign up and provide other details.

Conclusion & Discussion¶

There are several immediate trends that stand out when analyzing the immigration data provided by the UN. Since topics like immigration and asylum seeking are such intensely political issues, we decided to look into any potential external social pressures that might impact the rate refugees are accepted.

A consistent theme across all of the analyzed nations is that asylum seeking peoples spiked in the early years of the conflict. This growth then tapers to zero for each nation as time approaches 2022. Furthermore, UN mandated refugees started slowly and grew into the only method of migration by 2015. It is the opinion of the group that this shift was caused by initial lack of governmental programs to facilitate refugees, and as time went on programs were set in place to control inflows and uniformly classify Syrian migrants.

The nation of Iraq accepted remarkably few migrants. We believe that this is because of the United States invasion of the nation. While the invasion officially ended in 2012 prior to the beginning of our analysis, the analyzed event data indicated that life in Iraq was still significantly more inhospitable than other bordering nations. This was made especially apparent in the correlation matrix where traditionally violent events had a strong negative correlation to total refugee count. Lebanon and Jordan accepted more migrants proportional to their population than other nations, and as time approached 2022 were on a path of convergence. Turkey accepted considerably more refugees than the other countries. This is consistent with the group’s belief that securing refugee rights, a larger population, and a stronger economy would result in more migrants. The group was able to build a regression model for the migrant data that covered a portion of the variance, but external social factors ultimately limit the growth of migration and result in the plateaus. Migration quotas, caps, and lack of resources limit the natural growth of migrant populations. We believe that additional access to information, while a large ask, would’ve yielded stronger analysis. The limitations of bureaucratic government and war time data collection mean that tracking migrant populations on the minute level is especially difficult.
